      "comment_id" : 135542962,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "This does work for multi-module Maven projects, but you have to do this for every &quot;instance&quot; of the <code>target</code> directories, no matter which path is taken. Because Eclipse flattens all the Maven modules in its conception of the project (as you can see in the Package Explorer), you have to tag the same folder in multiple places. For instance, if you have nested modules <code>A&#47;B&#47;C</code> and you want to exclude the <code>A&#47;B&#47;C&#47;target</code> directory, you’ll also have to manually exclude <code>B&#47;C&#47;target</code>, <code>C&#47;target</code>.  Yes, this is horrible. And which is why I&#39;ll pay for IntelliJ"
    } ],
